        <section class="main-idea segment-opener" data-uuid="51645b6de1e64842881ffdd84ab9e4da">
            <article data-uuid="594112dd3bac416499e35f10627f076c">
                <h4 data-uuid="f369f3bb0c7e47659930e1e89e586ae1">Main Idea</h4>
                <p class="main-idea" data-uuid="ce1bbe95ea8c448ba1a722c77ac32b35">The effects of the war included prosperity and national pride.</p>
                <h2 data-uuid="58d60d3966fb47b0bc7cebcb0c9b7ceb">Effects of the War</h2>
                <div class="yellow-star-yellow-bar" data-uuid="b5938f290c1947c8a29db08edb8d70db"></div>
            </article>
        </section>
        <p data-uuid="f554a54c5a18422aa89e3c00a0437def"> Before the Battle of New Orleans, a group of New England Federalists gathered secretly at Hartford, Connecticut. At the <b><dfn title="Hartford Convention">Hartford Convention</dfn></b>, Federalists agreed to oppose the war and send delegates to meet with Congress. Before the delegates reached Washington, however, news arrived that the war had ended. Some critics now laughed at the Federalists, and the party lost much of its political power.</p>
        <h3 data-uuid="de579435461146d7ac69eaa4c49b297a">The Hartford Convention</h3>
        <p data-uuid="c7a51e8cfb1c4c9f94f202974cbe4da2">On December 15, 1814, delegates from the Massachusetts, Connecticut, Rhode Island, Vermont, and New Hampshire legislatures met in secret at the Old State House in Hartford. These delegates met for three weeks in order to draft a formal protest against the nation’s continued involvement in the War of 1812.<br />
        </p>
        <p data-uuid="95cc517f14984904a4dc289c85859566">The Federalists favored peace—and strong trade relations—with the British. They were angered over the economic devastation they were experiencing as a result of the Embargo Act of 1807 and subsequent congressional acts limiting trade. Rumors came forward that the Convention would call for New England’s secession from the United States. Most New England Federalists, however, held more moderate views and feared that even talk of secession might lead to a civil war.</p>
        <section class="historical-source nobg" data-uuid="3c4edba40c66464fbca497ec007130c2">
            <article class="box gradient" data-uuid="f3785f9210d9479c820cf017649092b8">
                <div class="header-element" data-uuid="621ecc858a324835912e12e6f02e6529">
                    <h2 class="label" data-uuid="26220149482743e08a8dc7f1d651a8c4"><b>Document-Based Investigation</b>   Historical Source</h2>
                </div>
                <div class="jonra" data-uuid="709bc0b3885a4acfbba79e5949623c84">
                    <h2 data-uuid="7f6981e4bec24e2cb16307f9d5a52d83">The Hartford Convention</h2>
                    <p class="source" data-uuid="f0b1ad52ddb44aa1bae45142ade55284">The Hartford Convention resulted in a declaration calling on the Federal Government to protect New England and to supply financial aid to New England’s badly battered trade economy. It also brought forth recommendations for Constitutional amendments, including a proposal that would limit the power of Congress to enforce an embargo for longer than sixty days.</p>
                </div>
